(Decision
    "Public contract verbs should be the client's domain actions — Query, Message, Configure, Register, etc. — not the database execution verbs (Assert/Mutate/Retract/Match/Subscribe/Validate). The signal-core 6 verbs describe what happens to state inside an engine; they belong at the execution layer, not the public-contract layer. Public contracts speak the language of what the client is asking the daemon to do; the daemon internally translates to whatever Sema operations the state-effect requires. This is the architectural direction; Candidate C from /125 (two-level) or B (six roots moved to Sema) is the right shape — the psyche's lean is the direction where the verb the client sends is the verb in the contract."
    "There are other things that might resolve into an assert that might resolve into a match in an engine somewhere, but that are not the signal that the client is trying to send. … entertain my point of view here to make sure that you aren't just agreeing with the technical debt. I really don't care about technical debt."
